speaker: CLEOPATRA
text_entry: SCENE V. Alexandria. MARK ANTONY's camp.

speaker: CLEOPATRA
text_entry: Trumpets sound. Enter MARK ANTONY and EROS; a Soldier meeting them

speaker: Soldier
text_entry: The gods make this a happy day to Antony!

speaker: MARK ANTONY
text_entry: Would thou and those thy scars had once prevail'd

speaker: MARK ANTONY
text_entry: To make me fight at land!

speaker: Soldier
text_entry: Hadst thou done so,

speaker: Soldier
text_entry: The kings that have revolted, and the soldier

speaker: Soldier
text_entry: That has this morning left thee, would have still

speaker: Soldier
text_entry: Follow'd thy heels.

speaker: MARK ANTONY
text_entry: Who's gone this morning?

speaker: Soldier
text_entry: Who!

speaker: Soldier
text_entry: One ever near thee: call for Enobarbus,

speaker: Soldier
text_entry: He shall not hear thee; or from Caesar's camp

speaker: Soldier
text_entry: Say 'I am none of thine.'

speaker: MARK ANTONY
text_entry: What say'st thou?

speaker: Soldier
text_entry: Sir,

speaker: Soldier
text_entry: He is with Caesar.

speaker: EROS
text_entry: Sir, his chests and treasure

speaker: EROS
text_entry: He has not with him.

speaker: MARK ANTONY
text_entry: Is he gone?

speaker: Soldier
text_entry: Most certain.

speaker: MARK ANTONY
text_entry: Go, Eros, send his treasure after; do it;

speaker: MARK ANTONY
text_entry: Detain no jot, I charge thee: write to him--

speaker: MARK ANTONY
text_entry: I will subscribe--gentle adieus and greetings;

speaker: MARK ANTONY
text_entry: Say that I wish he never find more cause

speaker: MARK ANTONY
text_entry: To change a master. O, my fortunes have

speaker: MARK ANTONY
text_entry: Corrupted honest men! Dispatch.--Enobarbus!

speaker: MARK ANTONY
text_entry: Exeunt
